RSTudio exercise 3: Logistic regression

library(tidyr); library(dplyr); library(ggplot2)

Reading the data

Let’s start by reading a prepared dataset “alcdata.csv” on alcohol consumption among Portuguese students:

alc <- read.csv("alcdata.csv")

Here are the dimensions of our data:

dim(alc)
## [1] 382  35

Now we can observe, that our dataset consists of 383 observations (students) and 35 variables. We can take a closer look at the variables by printing out the column names of the dataset:

colnames(alc)
##  [1] "school"     "sex"        "age"        "address"    "famsize"   
##  [6] "Pstatus"    "Medu"       "Fedu"       "Mjob"       "Fjob"      
## [11] "reason"     "nursery"    "internet"   "guardian"   "traveltime"
## [16] "studytime"  "failures"   "schoolsup"  "famsup"     "paid"      
## [21] "activities" "higher"     "romantic"   "famrel"     "freetime"  
## [26] "goout"      "Dalc"       "Walc"       "health"     "absences"  
## [31] "G1"         "G2"         "G3"         "alc_use"    "high_use"

From this group of variables I choose four (4) for my further analysis. These are sex (1), students address (2), going out with friends (3), and weekly studying time (4). Next I will explore and analyse these variables and their relationships with the level of alcohol consumption. My starting hypothesis is that the male sex (1) and going out with friends (3) will correlate positively with high alcohol consumption, and that weekly studying time (4) will effect negatively on alcohol consumption. In our data the address (2) variable is binominal: Urban and rural. This is a tough one since I can see it going both ways. In rural areas the compared absence of services and longer distances might create an environment that is very suitable for high alcohol consumption. On the other hand, the urban environment might also do the same.

Note on alcoholcomsumption: the variable alcohol use is cteated by combining and averaging the variables related to workday and weekend consumption on alcohol. These variable have numeric values from 1 - 5 (from very low to very high), and the variable for high alcohol consumption gives binary results when the value of alcohol use is either less (<) than 3 (FALSE) or above (>) 2 (TRUE).

Exploring the variables

Alcohol consumption and sex

Let’s star with the relationship between sex and alcohol consumption. Our data (382 observations) consists of 198 females and 184 males. Their respective numbers vs. alcohol consumption can be seen below:

mytable <- table(alc$high_use, alc$sex)
mytable
##        
##           F   M
##   FALSE 156 112
##   TRUE   42  72

Now we can observe that high alcohol consumption is, quantitatively speaking, more frequent among male students. To stress the same point from the relative point of view, we can also take a look at flollowing percentages:

prop.table(mytable, 2)
##        
##                 F         M
##   FALSE 0.7878788 0.6086957
##   TRUE  0.2121212 0.3913043

Now we can see that a little over 39% of male students count as high alcohol users. Among females the same number is circa 21%. The following box plot gives further information on the topic: Although the range of alcohol consumption among both sexes is close to each other, this is simply because of few outliers in the data concerning female students. There is also a big difference between median alcohol consumption values, and the male median is very close to the high usage limit (>2).

usesex <- ggplot(alc, aes(x =sex, y = alc_use, col = sex))
usesex + geom_boxplot()

What comes to my earlier hypothesis on the effect of sex on alcohol consumption, we can now conclude that the hypothesis was quite on point.

Rural and urban alcohol consumption

Next we are going to take a look on rural and urban alcohol consumption. My starting hypothesis was quite ambivalent on this one. Let’s see how the numners look like. First a quantitative look:

mytable2 <- table(alc$high_use, alc$address)
mytable2
##        
##           R   U
##   FALSE  50 218
##   TRUE   31  83

And then a relative one:

prop.table(mytable2, 2)
##        
##                 R         U
##   FALSE 0.6172840 0.7242525
##   TRUE  0.3827160 0.2757475

Now it seems clear that, in the context of our dataset, the rural environment is more fertile for higher alcohol consumption (~38% against urban ~28%). Here is also a box plot to further stress this same point:

useaddr <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = address, y = alc_use))
useaddr + geom_boxplot()

Going out with friends (to drink?)

Our third variable concerns sociality and going out with friends. My original hypothesis was that there is a strong connection eith alcohol and having a good time with friends. Now it seems that our data strongly agrees with me. Let’s observe this withthe help of bar plots:

counts <- table(alc$high_use, alc$goout)
barplot(counts,
  xlab="Goin out with friends", col=c("darkblue","red"), main = "Going out with friends and alcohol consumption",
  legend = rownames(counts), beside=TRUE)

Now we can see a strong development with the variable going out with friends rising from very low to very high, and finally over half of the students belonging to the last category are high alcohol users.

Weekly study time and alcohol consumption

Last but not least I was quite confident that we would see a clear connection with low work rate and high alcohol consumption, and a negative connection with high work rate and high consumption. First we take a look at the numbers:

mytable3 <- table(alc$high_use, alc$studytime)
mytable3
##        
##           1   2   3   4
##   FALSE  58 135  52  23
##   TRUE   42  60   8   4

From this we see that the for both groups of alcohol consumption the modes and medians are same. But by far the best way to illustrate the connection we are looking for is to observe the following percentages:

prop.table(mytable3, 2)
##        
##                 1         2         3         4
##   FALSE 0.5800000 0.6923077 0.8666667 0.8518519
##   TRUE  0.4200000 0.3076923 0.1333333 0.1481481

Here we can see a strong trend: Among students with lowest weekly study time the percentage of high alcohol consumers is 42%. On the other hand, among students with high weekly study time (3 or 4) we have significantly lower alocohol percentage numbers (~13% and ~15%). From this data we can also see the big drop in percentages between students with second lowest work rate and the second highest work rate (~17 percentage points).

Logistic regression

Next it’s time to fit a model with the binary variable of high alcohol consumption as the target variable. As explanatory variables we use the four variables mentioned above. Let’s see the summary of it:

model <- glm(high_use ~ sex + address + goout + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")
OR <- coef(model) %>% exp
OR
## (Intercept)        sexM    addressU       goout   studytime 
##   0.1091815   1.9200848   0.4828085   2.1737898   0.6117667

Now our coefficients resemble our analysis above. Our hypothesis concerning the “going out with friends” variable is again strongly supported. The estimated coefficient of 0.7765 can be interpreted as ratio of odds: In the context of this model the risk of high alcohol consumption doubles (rises by 117% to be more precise) by change of any one unit in the explanatory variable. Same applys with the “studytime” variable: This time our coefficent is negative or, interpreted as ratio of odds, it has value that is less than one, hence verifying our hypothesis that rise in studying time effects negatively on alcohol consumption. Because all of our variables have values other than one, they also have expected effects: Urban environment effects negatively and male sex effects positively on alcohol use. Here are confidence intervals for our odds ratios. Here we can see, for example, how the sex (male) variables high variance influeces the confidence interval:

CI <- confint(model) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
cbind(OR, CI)
##                    OR      2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.1091815 0.03260969 0.3471766
## sexM        1.9200848 1.15329428 3.2184771
## addressU    0.4828085 0.26707856 0.8727450
## goout       2.1737898 1.72868883 2.7723420
## studytime   0.6117667 0.43453305 0.8460957

Predictive power of our model

After our observations I decide to plot a new model, this time with only two explanatory variables “going out with friends” and “studying time”:

model2 <- glm(high_use ~ goout + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Now we can see how well our new model predicts high alcohol use:

probabilities <- predict(model2, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   247   21
##    TRUE     73   41

And here are the percentages:

table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table(2)
##         prediction
## high_use     FALSE      TRUE
##    FALSE 0.7718750 0.3387097
##    TRUE  0.2281250 0.6612903

No we can see that our model succeeds better at predicting low alcohol consumption than high alcohol consumption. Of all students rated as low alcohol consumers our model picks over 77%, nad the same number for high alcohol consumers is circa 66%. The again nearly 23% percent of our predicted low alcohol users are in reality high consumers. The number for predicted high alcohol users is nearly 34%. Finally we can compute the average number of wrong precitions, that is the training error, in our model:

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2460733

Here we can see that the proportion of incorrect predictions in our testing data is approximately 25%. The less is always better but the variance in our data of low and high alcohol users makes predicting very hard: We have high consumers in every different group of our variables, although we also found variables with quite good prediction power (for example the going out with friends variable). But all in all, in our original dataset of 382 observations we had 114 students considered as high alcohol users. That means that approximately 30% of our students are high alcohol users and our model predicted over 66% of them correctly. In my opinion this is a fearly good result and hard to beat with any simple guessing strategy,

The effect of this can be easily seen by comparing our earlier summary of the data with the summary below: The main difference is that all of the variables in our scaled variables have mean values of zero (0). Now we can more easily compare the variations, ranges, and constitutions between our variables, and, most importantly, plot their connections.

Now it’s time to concentrate on the per capita crime rate variable. Let’s start by creating a categorical value out of the crime variable of our new scaled dataset. We star by dividing our crime rate data into quantiles. The numbers are the same as in our latest summary minus the mean: ( Before that we must convert the data to a data frame format.)

scaledbos <- as.data.frame(scaledbos)
quant <- quantile(scaledbos$crim)
quant
##           0%          25%          50%          75%         100% 
## -0.419366929 -0.410563278 -0.390280295  0.007389247  9.924109610

Next we give names to our quantiles: Starting from the first (0-25%) the names of our new categories are “low”, “med_low” (25-50%), “med_high” (50-75%) and “high” (75-100%). Let’s take look how many observations fit under these categories:

crime <- cut(scaledbos$crim, breaks = quant, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
table(crime)
## crime
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127

Training and testing

Before dividing our data into train and test sets, we have to remove our old continuous variable and add our new categorical variable into our (scaled) dataset.

scaledbos <- dplyr::select(scaledbos, -crim)
scaledbos <- data.frame(scaledbos, crime)

Now we are ready to divide our prepared dataset into train and test sets. The train set will cover 80% of our data. The we remove the train set and the crime variable from our test set:

n <- nrow(scaledbos)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- scaledbos[ind,]
test <- scaledbos[-ind,]

Now let’s fit the LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) on the train set. We have the categorical crime rate as our target variable and all the other variables as explanatory variables. The plot looks as follows:

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}


classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)


plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1.6)

This plot again shows us the correlation between the variable “index of accessibility to radial highways” (rad) and higher crime rates. The LDA plot also clearly separates the two high crime rate classes (categories) from the two other crime rates, although some of the “med_high” observations are quite mixed with both the “low” and “med_low” groups. Now let’s do some predicting! (Just after we have saved the crime categories from the test set and removed the categorical crime variable from the test set.)

correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
tab <- table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
tab
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15      14        0    0
##   med_low    8      10       11    0
##   med_high   1       4       13    3
##   high       0       0        0   23

The above table shows the test dataset’s correct results vs. predicted results based on our training set. As we can see, our prediction is spot on with the highest category of crime rates, but then the amount of misclassifications starts rising. In overall, our prediction succeeds better with the two higher categories, but, as our LDA plot shows, the remaining to categories and part of the second highest category are more a lot more harder to separate from each other. Let’s conclude by calculating our models accuracy:

sum(diag(tab))/sum(tab)
## [1] 0.5980392

So our training models accuracy percent is circa 72%.

K-means clustering

Let’s finish with doing some k-means clustering to find the optimal number of categories in our dataset. In order to do this, we return our original scaled dataset.

library(MASS)
data("Boston")

And the we standardize…

scaled <- scale(Boston)

…and calculate the Euclidean distances:

dist_eu <- dist(scaled)
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970

To find the optimal number of clusters within our dataset, we look at how the total of within cluster sum of squares (WCSS) reacts to the changement of clusters. In order to do this, we set our maximum number of clusters as ten (10). The point of this analysis is to see when the value of WCSS drastically drops. Here is the plot:

library(ggplot2)
set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(scaled, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

The plot above shows that the optimum number of clusters for our data is two (2). Let’s run k-means algorithm with two (cluster) centers on the dataset. To give a more clear view and underline our poin, we produce the plot matrix only partially:

scaled <- as.data.frame(scaled)
km <-kmeans(scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(scaled[5:10], col = km$cluster)

Just to underline this, we can finish our analysis with a plot matrix with three (3) clusters. This looks significantly more messy and unoptimal:

scaled <- as.data.frame(scaled)
km <-kmeans(scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(scaled[5:10], col = km$cluster)

RStudio exercise 5: Dimensionality reduction techniques

Reading the data

This weeks data is provided by United Nations Development Programme, and it consists of different variables concerning human development. Our prepared dataset is a partial combination of two indices: The Human Development Index (HDI) and The Gender Inequality Index. As we can see from below, the dataset consists of 155 countries (observations) and 8 variables:

hdgii <- read.csv("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/human2.txt")
dim(hdgii)
## [1] 155   8

The variables measure per capita gross national income (GNI), life expectancy at birth (Life.Exp), expected years of schooling (Edu.Exp), maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor), adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth), Percetange of female representatives in parliament (Parli.F), the ratio of females with at least secondary education compared to men with secondary education (Edu2.FM), and the ratio of female and men populations in the labour force (Labo.FM). The values and ranges of all the variables can be observed below:

summary(hdgii)

Correlations

Next we are going to take a look at the correlations among our data. One simple and elightening way to examine this is to calculate a correlations matrix and to plot it. Our correlations plot colours negative correlations (0>x>-1) with different shades of red and positive correlations (-1>x>0) with shades of blue. Higher correlation values (the bigegr the distance is from the zero) are also presented with bigger dots:

library(dplyr)
library(corrplot)
library(GGally)
## 
## Attaching package: 'GGally'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     nasa
cor(hdgii) %>% corrplot(method="circle", type="upper", cl.pos="b", tl.pos="d", tl.cex = 0.6)

Judging by the above plot the two stand out correlations are the positive correlation for life expectancy at birth and expected years of schooling, and the negative one for maternal mortality ratio and life expectancy at birth. In my opinion these correlations fit very well with common sense presumptions about human development: When . It is also possible to examine these correlations in more precise manner by plotting the same correlations matrix with numerical values. This matrix plot confirms our previous assumptions concerning the strongest correlations: The exact numerical value for the correlation between life expectancy at birth and expected years of schooling is 0.789 and the correlation for maternal mortality ratio and life expectancy at birth is -0.857. The later is the highest correlation in our data. The lowest correlations are the values of ~ 0.0096 for “Labo.FM”" and “Edu2.FM”" and ~ -0.0071 for “Ado.Birth”" and “Parli.F”. These correlations are very small and the former one is nearly non-existant. All the correlations are presented in the matrix below:

ggpairs(hdgii)

PCA

PCA with unscaled variables

One way to analyse correlations in a given dataset is to limit its dimensions. This is useful when we don’t divide variables into target and explanatory variables. This means that we have to take into account all the dimensions and relationships in the dataset. And the bigger the dataset, the more messier and complex the full (especially visual) analysis. This is why it’s useful to resort to dimensionality reduction techniques such as principal component analysis (PCA). With PCA we can reduce any number of measured and correlated variables into a few independent components to account for the variation in the data. Let’s try this:

pca_hdgii <- prcomp(hdgii)
summary(pca_hdgii)
## Importance of components:
##                              PC1      PC2   PC3   PC4   PC5   PC6    PC7
## Standard deviation     1.854e+04 185.5219 25.19 11.45 3.766 1.566 0.1912
## Proportion of Variance 9.999e-01   0.0001  0.00  0.00 0.000 0.000 0.0000
## Cumulative Proportion  9.999e-01   1.0000  1.00  1.00 1.000 1.000 1.0000
##                           PC8
## Standard deviation     0.1591
## Proportion of Variance 0.0000
## Cumulative Proportion  1.0000

The above summary shows the results of PCA on our data. As we can see, our analysis gives us 8 components (PC1 to PC8), to match our 8 variables, to account for the variance. With PCA we can rank these components to account for the variance with only few components: This is the reduction part of our analysis. The thing that makes this kind of move effective is that the explanatory power of the component reduces with every added component. This can be seen form our summarys cumulative proportion -row, which reaches 1.00 (100%) with two components. But this is only relatively interesting since the proportion of variance of our PCA is very, very small: Our component collect together only the hundreth part of percent of the total variance, with the second component (PC2) doing most of the work. Something must be wrong here. The biplot with two most effective components has a lot to tell:

biplot(pca_hdgii, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"))

## Warning in arrows(0, 0, y[, 1L] * 0.8, y[, 2L] * 0.8, col = col[2L], length

Our PCA plot looks just as uninformative and cryptic as the summary suggested. The reason for this can be found from our datasets original summary. There we can see the large difference between mediums, ranges and values of our variables. The single largest value in our set is as big as 123124, which is the GNI score of Qatar. Compared to this the values of, for instance, “Labo.FM” and “Edu2.FM” are very small (both maximums are around 1.00). The immense value of the standard deviation of our PC2 (185.5219, see the summary) tells everything we need to know As we can see in the left hand side of our plot, there is big gap between any other country and Qatar, and the first component accounts only for this difference in GNI scores. The length and direction of the GNI vector tells the same thing. Most of our observations and vectors are grouped together and are imposible to observe. Only few outliers can be detected mainly because of their high GNI values and its effect on PC1, or because of high maternal mortality rates (Sierra Leone!). To get better and more fruitful results, we have to standardize our data.

Standardized

Let’s star with the summary of our new, tsandardized version of our old dataset. As we can see, the numbers look very different compared to our first summary: The mean values are set (scaled) to zero (0.0000) and the values are much closer to each other. But the main thing stays the same: The numbers account for the variance in our variables. The numbers can be seen from the summary below:

hdgii_scaled <- scale(hdgii)
summary(hdgii_scaled)

Now when the variables are scaled, we can present them using PCA. First the summary of the model:

pca_scaled <- prcomp(hdgii_scaled)
summary(pca_scaled)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6
## Standard deviation     2.0708 1.1397 0.87505 0.77886 0.66196 0.53631
## Proportion of Variance 0.5361 0.1624 0.09571 0.07583 0.05477 0.03595
## Cumulative Proportion  0.5361 0.6984 0.79413 0.86996 0.92473 0.96069
##                            PC7     PC8
## Standard deviation     0.45900 0.32224
## Proportion of Variance 0.02634 0.01298
## Cumulative Proportion  0.98702 1.00000

As we can see, with standardized data our numbers look very different. The standard deviation values are smaller and, most importantly, our components account for the overall variance in our data: Pc1 is responsible of circa 54 percent, and PC2 circa 16 percent. Together they account for nearly 70 percent of the complete variance. This is how our plot matrix looks like:

biplot(pca_scaled, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"))

Compared to the first biplot this plot really helps us to analyse our dataset. The vectors are all easy to separate, and their correlations (closeness directions and angles) are easy to see. We can, for example, see that the relative proportion of females in the labour force (Labo.FM) correlates more with female representation in parliament (Parli.F) than with any other variable. The secon component (CP2) accounts mainly for variance in these variables. The PC1 (x-axis) accounts for all the other variables. The spread of this axis shows clearly the high positive correlation between maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor) and adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth). The same principles of spatial closeness applys also for our observations (countries in this case). Once again the outliers are the easiest to spot: Rwanda with its unique history has high values on y-axis (PC2) and on this axis it’s the furthest away from countries such as Iran. Then again on x-axis (PC2) Iran is nearly at the opposite end compared to Niger, which has the lowest overall points in our dataset.

The reason why we choose to use MCA on this data lies in the fact that with the tea data we are dealing with discrete (factor) variables. The main idea and motivation is the same than earlier with PCA: We simply have too many numbers and variables going on! By reducing the dimensions we can again reveal connections and correspondences in our data. Let’s do this, but with fewer variables. We will use variables concerning tea types (“Tea”), the ways how people enjoy their tea (“How”), the price of customers’ tea(s) of choice (“price”), where people buy their tea (“where”), and do people enjoy their tea at luch (“lunch”). Let’s visualize our variables with bar plots so we can see the frequencies and levels of our chosen variables:

library(tidyr)

keep_columns <- c("Tea", "How", "price", "where", "lunch")

tea_time <- dplyr::select(tea, one_of(keep_columns))

gather(tea_time) %>% ggplot(aes(value)) + facet_wrap("key", scales = "free") + geom_bar() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 8))
## Warning: attributes are not identical across measure variables;
## they will be dropped

And now it’s time for MCA:

mca <- MCA(tea_time, graph = FALSE)
plot(mca, invisible=c("ind"), habillage = "quali")

Our MCA biplot looks quite similar with our ealier PCA plots: We have to dimensions on twho axis’, and we look for the spatial closeness of our observations. Our two dimensions retain circa 24 percentage of the overall variance of the data (12.64% + 11.35%), and the summary below shows that for the full 100 percantage 13 dimensions are needed. The summary also shows the effect of individual observations and individual categories on the dimensions. The table of categorical variables shows the links between variables and dimensions: As can be seen form the plot, the variables “price” (0.696) and “where” (0.720) have the stongest effect on dimension 1 presented on x-axis. Their overall spread on the plot accounts also highly on the variance of dimension 2 (y-axis).

RStudio exercise 6: Analysis of longitudinal data

Let’s download the data!

We are going to start our analysis section with introducing our prepared data set. I have already mentioned few thing about our this weeks data sets in the wrangling exercise. If we comparethe set that was created in that former exercise, we see that some of the variables have changed:

BPRSL <- read.csv("bprsl.csv")
str(BPRSL)

So let’s start with few remedial moves. We have to do two things: First we change our “treatment” and “subject” variables back to factors, and then we change our “weeks” variable from factors to characters. After these chanes it’s time to glimpse the data:

BPRSL$treatment <- factor(BPRSL$treatment)
BPRSL$subject <- factor(BPRSL$subject)
BPRSL$weeks <- as.character(BPRSL$weeks)

glimpse(BPRSL)

Analysis with RATS

Perhaps the best way to start investigating a new data set is to produce it graphically. Sow let’s plot our data! We start with displaying all the individual rats in our data and their respecting weights over time. We do this in three plots so we can also analyse the values and varitions among all of the three groups in our data set. The plots look like this:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = Weight, linetype = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(225), max(628)))

These three plots show us very conveniently some main characteristic in our data. First of all there is a clear difference between each of our groups: The group number one has significantly lower weight range and less variability than the other groups. In overall the trend is that the average weights rise with the groups. In the second group there seems to be one outlier which is completely in its own class. From the summary below we can see that the individual with the lowest weight in our data has a value of 225.0 (this individual belongs to the first group). Compared to this our highest observed value is as high 628.0. This individual belongs to the secong group and it certainly effects the analysis concerning the whole group.

summary(RATSL$Weight)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   225.0   267.0   344.5   384.5   511.2   628.0
